      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\sin(\theta) = \dfrac{x}{2}</m> for <m>-\dfrac{\pi}{2} \lt \theta \lt \dfrac{\pi}{2}</m>,
          find an expression for <m>\cos(2\theta)</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>1 - \dfrac{x^{2}}{2}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\tan(\theta) = \dfrac{x}{7}</m> for <m>-\dfrac{\pi}{2} \lt \theta \lt \dfrac{\pi}{2}</m>,
          find an expression for <m>\sin(2\theta)</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\dfrac{14x}{x^{2} + 49}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\sec(\theta) = \dfrac{x}{4}</m> for <m>0 \lt \theta \lt \dfrac{\pi}{2}</m>,
          find an expression for <m>\ln|\sec(\theta) + \tan(\theta)|</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\ln |x + \sqrt{x^{2} + 16}| - \ln(4)</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that <m>\cos^{2}(\theta) - \sin^{2}(\theta) = 2\cos^{2}(\theta) - 1 = 1 - 2\sin^{2}(\theta)</m> for all <m>\theta</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\theta</m> be a Quadrant III angle with <m>\cos(\theta) = -\dfrac{1}{5}</m>.
          Show that this is not enough information to determine the sign of
          <m>\sin\left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)</m> by first assuming <m>3\pi \lt \theta \lt \dfrac{7\pi}{2}</m> and then assuming
          <m>\pi \lt \theta \lt \dfrac{3\pi}{2}</m> and computing <m>\sin\left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)</m> in both cases.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Without using your calculator,
          show that <m>\dfrac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{3}}}{2} = \dfrac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
