          of <xref ref="doubleangleex">Example</xref>,
          we wrote <m>\cos(3\theta)</m> as a polynomial in terms of <m>\cos(\theta)</m>.
          In <xref ref="cosine4theta">Exercise</xref>,
          we had you verify an identity which expresses
          <m>\cos(4\theta)</m> as a polynomial in terms of <m>\cos(\theta)</m>.
          Can you find a polynomial in terms of <m>\cos(\theta)</m> for
          <m>\cos(5\theta)</m>? <m>\cos(6\theta)</m>?
          Can you find a pattern so that
          <m>\cos(n\theta)</m> could be written as a polynomial in cosine for any natural number <m>n</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
